title: (3/8) Why did Cyle major in Communications?
(4/8) Why did Cyle get an emphasis in film?
Meet Fern!
description:
Hey, it's Fern! Fern's one of the film professors who teaches some of the labs, as well as the one in charge of maintaining the TV Studio, equipment, and all of that for the film department.

He's a cool dude. Don't piss him off, though. Just make sure you take care of the equipment and he won't hurt you! ;)

title: Dogs!
description:
This is Fern's dog, but a few different professors in the COMM department have dogs and bring them to campus. 

Sometimes you'll see them roaming around the halls, other times, you'll see them walking around campus. A lot of the times, it's nice to come by and talk to professors AND pet dogs. As a dog lover, I take this as a win-win situation.

title: Working at Media Services
description:
Media Services was the first place I started working on campus.

When they first interviewed me, they asked me questions I thought were trick questions, like "a professor\'s having problems with showing a picture, what do you do?"

I answered "just unplug and plug in the HDMI?" thinking I wouldn\'t get the job.

I got the job.

title: Casting Call Flyer
description:
Some of the upper-division production classes have us work on larger, term-long projects, which involves us getting used to the entire production pipeline.

We learn to take on the roles of directors, producers, screenwriters, etc., and of course part of that is going through the process of finding actors. This is a casting call flyer for the big film project I'm currently working on.

title: Spring On-Site Shadowing Program
description:
This is one of the experiences I got that I think is pretty invaluable. Talking to someone from the industry really is different from just hearing what it's about in abstract.

We would go to the studios and see what was happening while also talking to someone who was an alumni at SCU, learn about what it's like to work in this industry.

title: Lights control
description:
The TV Studio is equipped with a variety of studio lights, all connected to and manipulateable by this control panel! 

The standard lights are on right now, but when shoots go on, lighting is really important to both capturing the right feel and creating the right sense of depth on the subjects. Under the covers are a bunch of sliders that control which lights are on, how bright each light is turned to, etc.

title: Green Screen
description:
The TV is also equipped with a green screen wall! 

For projects that involve special effects or rendered backgrounds, students can set up recording sessions to use the green screens. The wrinkle-less green material paired with the illuminating lighting equipment make for great bases for SFX!

title: Studio Set
description: Attached to the TV studio is a Studio Set students can use for their projects if they choose to. While it's a nice set and well lit, it's also somewhat small and limited, so most of the time students choose to film at on-location sets for their film projects. However, it's still a set film students can use if they choose to!

title: Getting Familiar with Film Equipment
description:
SCU was the first time I ever dealt with film equipment. One of the first few times I really paid attention in class, mostly because I didn't want to break thousands of dollars of equipment. I just got here after all.

The COMM department has a lot of gear for us to get familiar with, from cameras, to lights, to mics and mixers. The C100s are definitely a piece of equipment I'm always too afraid to touch. They're cool though.

title: TV Studio Hallway
description:
While a variety of classes and offices are held in Vari, entering the Vari TV Studio Hallway is almost it's own world! 

Though the hallway is unlocked during class hours, after standard class hours this hallway becomes locked to even other regular Communications students. However, if you're enrolled in a film class, you'll have key card access to both the building AND the TV Studio Hallway even after hours!

This is where you'll run into a lot of the film professors and other students learning about film.

title: Fern's Labs
description: There are a few different professors teaching a few different film labs in this room, but when Fern (who Cyle ran into outside) teaches a lab, especially if it's in the morning, he'll try to get the class's energy levels up with some music!

title: Film Labs
description:
One of the main things this room is used for is to conduct Film Labs! 

To help students during editing labs, the computers in the room (as well as the computers in the Edit Bays!) are equipped with decorated keyboards that show editing shortcuts for Avid Media Composer -- the industry standard video editing program!

There are also a variety of production labs in this room, where students can learn to set up cameras, lights, and other film equipment!

title: What are the Communication professors like?
Main Story Thread (8 parts)
description:
These tags explore Cyle's story of majoring in Communications and finding passion in screenwriting.

There are 8 total parts that cover Cyle's story.

title: More about Cyle
description: Blue tags are optional tags from Cyle expanding on his life at SCU past the main story.

title: More about SCU
description: Red tags are optional tags providing additional related information about SCU not specific to Cyle.

title: Audio Video Control Room
description:
Students who choose to use the Studio Set are also able to monitor their filming in a separate audio and video control room!

Not many students use the Studio Set or AV Control Room, as most of the time students choose to film at on-location sets for their film projects, but they often take portable sound mixers with them to sets.

title: Resources at Media Services
description:
Most of the work Cyle does with Media Services is customer service and helping professors, but students can also rent out adaptors and Edit Bays in the library. 

The Library Edit Bays are fully equipped, sound proof, and have a huge computer monitor, microphone, presenter stand, AND VR headset, but not many students know about it to use it. They're really cool though.

title: VARI HALL Classrooms
description:
There are also other classes held in VARI hall that aren't necessarily film classes, though they are generally classes in the communications department. 

Most of the classrooms in Vari are also equipped with a cameras and sound systems for Zoom setups, which can't be said about all of the rooms and buildings on campus!

title: Game Studies Meetings
description:
This room is a general meeting room in the building, and I think they've been holding information sessions in here for people who become COMM students to get caught up on what they'll be doing and need to do.

I would meet up with a Game Studies Research group in here, sitting around like a roundtable discussion. It was the most chaotic place i have ever entered in my entire life. If you want to talk about hot blooded debates over any video game related questions, here's the place. 

They're really passionate people, but it's a good thing it only happens once a week. There's too much energy in that room.

title: Production Practice
description: While a lot of the practice with filming and editing happens during the lab sessions, depending on the class, students might also get the opportunity during lecture classes to learn, practice, and familiarize themselves with equipment available to them!

title: The Godfather
description:
Of course I've had to watch a lot of different things for classes, but I watched A LOT of The Godfather. Both for adaptations class (to learn how to properly adapt an existing property to the screen) but also for screenwriting (to just break down how to write a good script).

Those two classes rewired my brain. I can't read a book anymore without thinking "how would I adapt this to the big screen?" and any time I watch ANYTHING, I see the screenplay in my brain, almost like subtitles.

title: Editing with Music
description: Like a lot of editors, Cyle often likes to put on some background music on in the room to work to. He personally likes to listen to songs from musicals while editing, like Le Miserables for example, which you can hear in the room right now!

title: Hungry Boys
description:
Check out the first video project I ever worked on: Hungry Boys!

This film was made for an assignment every student who has taken COMM 30 (Intro to Filmmaking) us familiar with, where the goal is to tell a complete story with only 12 shots.

title: COMM 135 - Editing
description: The film department offers a variety of courses that dig into different types of films and different aspects of film production, including a course all about editing and editing techniques!

title: YouTube Algorithm
description: This is a video essay I wrote and edited for one of my COMM classes, specifically my technology and media class. In it, I explore the dynamic between YouTube and content creators and how content creators take advantage of the algorithm.

title: Edit Bays
description:
Students in production classes have 24/7 access to 8 private edit bays!

All rooms come equipped with a multi-screen setup, soundboard, speakers, labeled keyboard, microphone, and dimmable lights! 

The actual systems are standard Macs all fitted with Avid Media Composer and the Adobe Creative Cloud. When enrolled in a production course, students will also receive a login account for a locally hosted Nexus server to store their video footage and projects, allowing for more media storage space and easier project transfer from bay to bay.
